SSDD = Seven Segment Display Display

TM1640 ($0.13/ea from JLCPCB assembly warehouse)

144pcs common anode 7 segment displays (the TM1640 supports common cathode too but
the PCB is wired for the common anode configuration)

CHECKLIST:
	[ ] Real time clock
	[ ] Print out actual size KiCad PCB and make sure components fit. Measure
	    board width/height to make sure printed size is correct.
	      - pushbutton footprints
	      - 7 segment display footprints
	[ ] Check 7 segment display width/height tolerance and adjust F.Courtyard
	    outline accordingly.
	    The silkscreen is currently the exact width/height according to the
	    datasheet (the outer edges of the silkscreen rect are the exact boundry
	    of the part). The F.Courtyard rect is exactly on the exact datasheet
	    width/height border, but that needs updating once the tolerances are
	    measured on the physical parts.
	[ ] Make sure footprints are right (TM1640 comes in several: SSOP, SOP, SOIC)
	[ ] Double check 7 segment display footprint, measure with calipers. The
	    current one is just random from the internet, could be wrong.
	[ ] Validate switch footprint
	[ ] Also double check 7 segment display pin numbering with multimeter/light up
	    each individual segment
	[ ] Make sure chips go on opposite side of board from segments
	[ ] Some datasheets seem to mention different addresses (upper nibble
	    being 0xc instead of 0x0), try both if 0 doesn't work (no hardware
	    changes needed)
	[ ] Attiny861-20su has builtin pullup resistors for buttons
	[ ] Debounce buttons in software
	[ ] Try putting black film (window tint? privacy tint?) over front to see
	    if it masks the gaps and inactive segments. (What's something less
	    opaque than window tint but still a tiny bit opaque?)
	[ ] Mounting holes?
	[X] Pushbuttons for setting time:
	    (ordered from ebay)
	      - "set/select": press to initiate setting mode, and accept current
	        parameter in setting mode.
	      - "next": press to increment current parameter
	      - "previous": press to decrement current parameter
	    If not enough GPIOs, can dual-purpose some GPIOs that go to TM1640
	    DIN pins (just don't clock them while the GPIOs are in input mode).
